fields.question_text: A business leader can only be evaluated by business performance metrics
A business leader must always prioritize actions that improve return on invested capital, above any other outcome
A leader is only as good as the technical knowledge they bring to the business
Asking for help signals that you don't know how to do your job
Before making a decision, I always consult information from other people who have been in a similar position to make sure I understand the full implications of my actions
Employees come to work to earn a salary, not because of a shared vision or shared values with those they work with
I am happy to dedicate the time it takes to learn things properly
I frequently ask other people how I'm performing in my role
I need to know someone on a personal level before I consider asking them for any sort of help
I prioritize spending time focusing on activities where I can directly act to achieve a tangible business outcome versus working with others to achieve their goals
I rarely compromise when making business decisions because I'm usually the most well-informed on the topic
I set a lot of goals knowing that I will only achieve some of them
I'm comfortable learning quickly even if that means I miss some of the details
Ideas from more experienced team members should be valued more than ideas from those with less experience
Individual employees must be supervised closely, or they will not perform as well as they could
It's important to punish mistakes, otherwise they'll keep happening
Its more important for me to know one area of my business really well, as opposed to a little bit about every part of the business
Leaders are born, not made - they either have the talent and ability or don't
It's more important to be acquainted with a lot of people than to have deep connections with a few people
Problem solving is an individual activity that requires deep thinking alone
The only people who have valuable advice to offer are those who operate in the same sector, location, or industry
The people I manage are better equipped at making decisions than I am because they have the best information at hand
There is a correct answer to every problem in business
When it comes to our work, 100% certainty is a fantasy
You can only be successful if you know the 'right people'
